My doctor told me it was ok to give tylenol if I felt my baby was uncomfortable or in pain. I also remember hearing that fevers/high body temp helps fight infection. Is that true?
So here is my question. Is giving my baby tylenol for a low grade fever preventing my baby from being able to fight off his sickness by lowering his temperature? Am I just prolonging his sickness? Is it better to just let the fever run its course? At what point should I be giving tylenol? I've read several medical articles and it seems like the evidence is very inconclusive. What are your thoughts?🤔🤔💗

snippet.textDisplay: Dr. Mike - I agree with many of the points you make in this video and am so happy that, as a medical professional, you are and have always been a strong advocate for mental health. As you allude to, there is a LOT of research suggesting that for many disorders (like ADHD, anxiety disorders, and even depression to a certain extent) CBT and NOT pharmacological treatments are first line therapies. Despite this, there are still many family doctors who prescribe medications like psychostimulants and benzodiazepines - both highly addictive - at the first sign of a kid not concentrating or an adult having mild anxiety. On an anecdotal level, I went to SEVERAL family medicine doctors over the course of YEARS when I was struggling with depression, anxiety, and anorexia and (a) not one did any sort of mental health screening and (b) none prescribed me medication or referred me even when I specifically complained of mood changes, extreme weight loss, and insomnia. As such, I see where Lady Gaga was going because while there are some family doctors who HAVE undergone extensive training and FREQUENTLY screen for mental disorders, there are also many who just seem to lack the expertise and knowledge to be able to appropriately care for patients with mental disorders and/or do not refer patients who need to be referred.

snippet.textDisplay: I understand where you're coming from, but I also understand where she's coming from. When you consider antidepressants only work for 40% of patients and also a GP is not the ones that diagnose mental illness, it is psychiatrists. So, even though we are trained to give someone that is displaying depressive symptoms a script to psychiatric medications - it should be more important to get them booked in with someone that is properly qualified to diagnose and treat mental health disorders thoroughly. So yes, if someone is in crisis and they need that bandaid fix to think properly, a script would be in order, but more importantly they need a professional capable of walking someone through the journey of self discovery and management of a lifelong illness. Medication does not cure mental illness.

snippet.textDisplay:
I was told for primary care vs mental health professional for mental health diagnoses/prescriptions, if there are multiple possibilities for what's going on and the wrong treatment could make it worse they should see a mental health specialist, but normally a primary care doctor can handle it, and often after a differential diagnosis they still can handle things.
My first anti-depressant was prescribed by my primary care provider, as was my second round after I was off it for a while due to lack of funds. Then that second doctor decided that with depression and anxiety and possible adhd and massive life stressors, he didn't feel comfortable addressing more than the basic depression and anxiety and referred me to a mental health specialist. I was a more complex case. But I know people who don't have insurance or have limited insurance as you described, who can only see their regular doctor and can't go to a specialist, but they still get good care.

And on the topic of self-diagnosis, if a friend mentions something I know from personal experience is a notable symptom of something like depression, I'll suggest they mention it to their doctor but discourage self-diagnosis normally. But with no access to care, self-diagnosis enables someone to try to learn coping skills for that problem to get by until they can get some sort of care. Sadly, lacking access to even primary care is a very real issue for some people.

snippet.textDisplay:
Here in Denmark we have one of the world's best medical sectors physical as well as psychiatric. Its still very tough, because one to one conversational therapy is something you need to pay for by yourself. But everything physical except dental issues is provided by the state. This makes it very easy for us as citizens to go for checkups and call on help from our primary care doctors. Our Primary care doctors are as all other doctors trained in therapeutic conversations and use of medicine for psychiatric purposes.

In my case, I pay for my own therapist, I find it works better for me than the group therapy programmes provided by the state. My primary care doctor, however was the first to see the signs of anxiety and get me on medication that instantly helped me. She follows up once every three months and changes my medication depending on my needs, she follows me very closely in my medicinal use, making sure I dont get an addiction or lose control. Furthermore she always takes her time, listening to what I go through with my therapist and providing holistic counsel taking into account my daughter, my husband, my studies and the general realities of life - reminding me what is normal, and what is not. During rough times I use both my therapist and my doctor, but during less hard times, my doctor is more than adequate in handling my therapeutic consults.
My husband had a depression, but never went to therapy, because it was a mild depression. He was prescribed antidepressants and consults with his doctor every 2 weeks, a few months later and he had worked through it. He didnt need a specialist, he just needed his primary care doctor.

You should always be using your primary care doctor as the most central help in your life. They are trained in this and they know you. If you are uncomfortable with your doctor, find a new one - it is ESSENTIAL that you have complete confidence in your doctor. They are our guardian angels and should always stand right behind you protecting your body and mind from harm - that is the essence of their job.

In my opinion, and I'm not a doctor, you are both right and very wrong. Yes, primary health care professionals should be able to give treatment for mental health problems however, you are wrong about how your primary care provider knows you better than a specialist and should therefore be able to provide a good treatment. Where I live doctors easily have 2000+ patients and don't even know the name of most patients... Then when going to see those doctors, you get 10 minutes per appointment to tell them what's wrong with you and within those 10 minutes they decide what kind of medications they can put you on... I mean, I'm sorry, but HOW? 10 minutes is not enough to decide on a treatment, 10 minutes is not even enough to scratch the surface of what is actually going on. And because of that, a lot of people get medicated for the wrong thing. Incorrect medication can have extremely negative consequences for the patients.

So, if after those 10 min, my primary care provider would choose to start a diagnostic process before deciding on treatment then I would easily trust them with mental health care but as long as they keep prescribing within 10 minutes and without an actual diagnosis, I won't trust them...

Really good points being made here. I can only offer a personal perspective but in Australia very few psychiatrists are covered in our healthcare system, the closest one to me is three-four hours drive away and they have waiting lists that take months.

If not for my family general practitioner prescribing me anti-depressants to manage the harmful symptoms of my more complex mental health disorder the wait would be so much riskier. Even if you have something more complex your family doctor can do their best to minimise the harmful factors impacting your life (and potentially getting worse with no treatment) until you can get access to a psychiatrist.
